that A has been much more tampered with than B.

Fortunately, as has been said above, Durga repeats every word of the
Niruktla in his commentary, so that the text of the Niruktg 'in toto can be
reproduced from his commentary alone. - This commentary therefore serves
the purpose of a manuscript of the Nirukta and supplies valuable information
ahout the condition of the text in its author's time. Durga does not
recognize the parisiste as an integral part of the Niruktu, as in fact he is
even unaware of its existence. Thus his commentary preserves the text
of the Nirukte as current before the addition of the parisistæ. Further,
it derives great value from the fact that Durga dlsphys critical judgement
in the adoptlon of readings in the text, while giving variants and adding
critical notes on them. For example, in N. i. 2, ho "0४05 अयुगपत् but

 


